00:16:57.865 --> 00:17:00.025
so I will ask it.

00:17:00.025 --> 00:17:02.826
I'll also stick it in the chat here,

00:17:02.826 --> 00:17:04.865
but I think this is a great one to ask

00:17:04.865 --> 00:17:09.106
for anybody who is trying to advocate for a tool.

00:17:09.106 --> 00:17:12.226
It says, how do you get your team to switch to Shiny

00:17:12.226 --> 00:17:13.666
instead of Tableau?

00:17:13.666 --> 00:17:15.585
Tableau makes me sad.

00:17:15.585 --> 00:17:16.625
I will replace Tableau

00:17:16.625 --> 00:17:19.826
with like any point and click dashboard creation tool.

00:17:19.826 --> 00:17:23.826
Do you have any tips on advocating for Shiny as a tool?

00:17:25.625 --> 00:17:28.625
Or maybe like why it's difficult for leadership

00:17:28.625 --> 00:17:30.865
to wrap their head around using an open source tool

00:17:30.865 --> 00:17:32.865
that's code first like Shiny?

00:17:32.865 --> 00:17:36.226
Yeah, I think the code first is probably the biggest hurdle.

00:17:36.226 --> 00:17:37.226
Yeah, yeah.

00:17:37.226 --> 00:17:40.625
Yeah, so getting people to write code

00:17:40.625 --> 00:17:43.185
who don't write code is, you know,

00:17:43.425 --> 00:17:46.506
it's, I think you have to really get them

00:17:46.506 --> 00:17:48.986
to kind of build on, you know,

00:17:50.546 --> 00:17:52.625
getting them to build on successes.

00:17:52.625 --> 00:17:54.585
I think that, you know, we use the phrase a lot,

00:17:54.585 --> 00:17:57.025
like let them eat cake first, right?

00:17:57.025 --> 00:17:59.305
You know, I think that part of the reason

00:17:59.305 --> 00:18:00.946
that Tableau, Power BI, all these, you know,

00:18:00.946 --> 00:18:02.786
these point and click kind of GUI interfaces

00:18:02.786 --> 00:18:05.025
are so popular is because, you know,

00:18:05.025 --> 00:18:07.185
for the majority of people using them,

00:18:07.185 --> 00:18:10.465
they not only have attached in their mind

00:18:10.465 --> 00:18:13.106
a certain like expediency and a timeline

00:18:13.865 --> 00:18:14.706
in which these things are built,

00:18:14.706 --> 00:18:16.826
but they have a mental model for how, you know,

00:18:16.826 --> 00:18:19.226
like if I want to build a dashboard or I want to,

00:18:20.345 --> 00:18:22.506
you know, with Tableau, it's, you know,

00:18:22.506 --> 00:18:24.946
I want to build this thing, I want to have maximum

00:18:24.946 --> 00:18:27.666
kind of like, you know, what they perceive

00:18:27.666 --> 00:18:29.546
is I want to be able to customize it.

00:18:29.546 --> 00:18:30.905
And then I want to be able to share it quickly

00:18:30.905 --> 00:18:32.585
with whoever's asked for it, right?

00:18:32.585 --> 00:18:34.826
And I think that for them, the biggest hurdle

00:18:34.826 --> 00:18:37.425
is I'm going to go from a mental model

00:18:37.425 --> 00:18:41.506
and process and timeline that I'm vaguely, you know,

00:18:41.506 --> 00:18:43.826
comfortable predicting outcomes with to,

00:18:43.826 --> 00:18:46.706
I'm going to go learn a syntax and a language

00:18:46.706 --> 00:18:48.706
in which, you know, there's just a total uncertainty

00:18:48.706 --> 00:18:51.345
on how quickly they'll be able to develop,

00:18:51.345 --> 00:18:53.946
to deliver and develop the same product,

00:18:53.946 --> 00:18:55.946
you know, products, the same outcomes.

00:18:55.946 --> 00:18:58.266
So I think that it kind of takes baby steps

00:18:58.266 --> 00:19:00.946
in getting them comfortable with doing anything in code

00:19:00.946 --> 00:19:02.546
versus point and click.

00:19:02.546 --> 00:19:05.506
And once they can kind of see the ecosystem around,

00:19:05.506 --> 00:19:08.266
like why we use code, you know,

00:19:08.266 --> 00:19:10.786
the fact that you can be version controlled,

00:19:10.786 --> 00:19:12.025
the fact that you can collaborate with it,

00:19:12.025 --> 00:19:13.826
the fact that, you know, nothing,

00:19:13.826 --> 00:19:18.706
no GUI is ever going to be a full language, right?

00:19:18.706 --> 00:19:20.226
Because language gives us,

00:19:21.946 --> 00:19:24.106
I'm going to forget what Willem Voeltz said about language,

00:19:24.106 --> 00:19:26.185
that it's infinite,

00:19:27.345 --> 00:19:30.786
infinite, you know, kind of outcomes with finite,

00:19:31.986 --> 00:19:32.826
you know, objects.

00:19:32.826 --> 00:19:34.266
So it's the fact that a language gives you the ability

00:19:34.266 --> 00:19:35.986
to literally create kind of anything

00:19:35.986 --> 00:19:38.266
with endless combinations of its, you know,

00:19:38.266 --> 00:19:39.465
verbs and grammar.

00:19:39.465 --> 00:19:40.666
And that's why, you know,

00:19:40.666 --> 00:19:43.946
no matter how many things you put into a GUI interface,

00:19:43.946 --> 00:19:48.386
you're still, it's, you have two clicks with a mouse, right?

00:19:48.386 --> 00:19:51.025
That's all you can do is click or not, right?

00:19:51.025 --> 00:19:52.986
And the fact that you have a language,

00:19:52.986 --> 00:19:54.425
like ggplot2 is a perfect example of,

00:19:54.425 --> 00:19:56.786
not only is it a full grammar

00:19:56.786 --> 00:20:00.145
of how to build beautiful visualizations,

00:20:00.145 --> 00:20:01.986
but the more you use ggplot2,

00:20:01.986 --> 00:20:04.745
the more you can pick up any graph or look at any chart

00:20:04.745 --> 00:20:06.345
and understand it better,

00:20:06.386 --> 00:20:09.025
because you have a language of understanding graphs

00:20:09.025 --> 00:20:12.025
that you didn't have prior to programming with that,

00:20:12.025 --> 00:20:13.185
but that's intense.

00:20:13.185 --> 00:20:14.666
And, you know,

00:20:14.666 --> 00:20:16.706
computer programming languages are the same way,

00:20:16.706 --> 00:20:17.546
you know, when it comes,

00:20:17.546 --> 00:20:19.905
R has its origin in statistics

00:20:19.905 --> 00:20:23.546
and it isn't long before you're doing statistics with R

00:20:23.546 --> 00:20:28.546
that, you know, the programming in many ways

00:20:28.625 --> 00:20:31.145
complements your statistical knowledge, right?

00:20:31.145 --> 00:20:32.786
So the two kind of go hand in hand.

00:20:32.786 --> 00:20:34.906
And I think that when it comes to getting people

00:20:34.906 --> 00:20:38.425
to switch over to a syntax based tool,

00:20:38.425 --> 00:20:40.425
it's just them kind of unlocking the ability

00:20:40.425 --> 00:20:42.105
of the language versus, you know,

00:20:42.105 --> 00:20:45.066
kind of resisting that, you know, that point and click,

00:20:45.985 --> 00:20:46.826
which like I said,

00:20:46.826 --> 00:20:49.225
most of the time it's based around, you know,

00:20:49.225 --> 00:20:50.466
whatever, wherever you're working,

00:20:50.466 --> 00:20:53.625
that organization has timelines and expectations for,

00:20:53.625 --> 00:20:55.346
you know, I want a dashboard and I want to, you know,

00:20:55.346 --> 00:20:57.305
with these particular features

00:20:57.305 --> 00:21:00.225
and the person who's delivering it in Power BI or Tableau,

00:21:00.225 --> 00:21:01.066
like I said,

00:21:01.066 --> 00:21:04.185
they can confidently deliver something within that timeline.

00:21:04.185 --> 00:21:07.545
And so the opportunity cost of giving up a known tool

00:21:07.545 --> 00:21:08.386
with timeline,

00:21:08.386 --> 00:21:09.506
even though it doesn't have some of the features

00:21:09.506 --> 00:21:12.066
that we know that like Shiny would have,

00:21:12.066 --> 00:21:14.826
you know, it's going to an unknown,

00:21:14.826 --> 00:21:17.466
both with the syntax and with the actual application.

00:21:18.906 --> 00:21:19.906
Awesome. Thank you.

