00:22:35.925 --> 00:22:38.566
I've basically decided to come in

00:22:38.566 --> 00:22:40.326
with a bit of a technical question.

00:22:41.285 --> 00:22:43.725
As a fellow lover of Shiny

00:22:43.725 --> 00:22:45.485
or somebody who enjoys kind of playing with it

00:22:45.485 --> 00:22:49.625
and doing stuff, I have a question about modules.

00:22:49.625 --> 00:22:53.365
So when I write code in R, which is what I write primarily in

00:22:53.365 --> 00:22:54.766
I love writing functions.

00:22:54.766 --> 00:22:56.446
I love vectorizing things,

00:22:56.446 --> 00:22:58.446
generalizing my code as much as I can,

00:22:58.446 --> 00:23:01.526
but I can't seem to wrap my mind around modules

00:23:01.526 --> 00:23:06.326
even though I do have a pretty solid basic understanding

00:23:06.326 --> 00:23:07.886
of reactivity.

00:23:07.886 --> 00:23:10.886
So I'm wondering if you might explain modules like I'm five.

00:23:11.925 --> 00:23:15.766
Yeah, modules are to your Shiny app

00:23:15.766 --> 00:23:20.766
what your folder directory is like in your operating system.

00:23:21.846 --> 00:23:25.245
So the best way to think about modules

00:23:25.245 --> 00:23:28.326
is that when you create another namespace,

00:23:29.165 --> 00:23:30.006
it's really not that complicated.

00:23:30.006 --> 00:23:33.406
It just appends the name of that namespace

00:23:33.406 --> 00:23:37.406
into the applications like reactive model.

00:23:37.406 --> 00:23:40.006
So when you, the simplest is like,

00:23:40.006 --> 00:23:43.006
if you have some input module

00:23:43.006 --> 00:23:44.966
and then some output module that has a graph, right?

00:23:44.966 --> 00:23:47.805
And so you're collecting like three dropdown inputs

00:23:47.805 --> 00:23:50.646
with this input module and you're shooting it over

00:23:50.646 --> 00:23:53.406
to your graphing function and at the output.

00:23:53.406 --> 00:23:54.245
So,

00:23:55.452 --> 00:23:59.212
Namespace collision is what you're trying to avoid with modules, right, because it's all one

00:23:59.212 --> 00:24:04.492
namespace with just an app.r file. And when you append a namespace that is just literally

00:24:06.125 --> 00:24:29.125
It's like, what's the string function where you're just you're pasting together the name of the namespace into the output, right? So your input IDs, you know, let's say you have input x, y, and z, and you have a module that's inputs becomes inputs dash x input that y input stacked z.

00:24:29.125 --> 00:24:45.125
And the reason that you have these, you know, these appended namespaces, it's back to the folder and directory is you can't have two folders with the same name in the same directory, right? You can't in your root directory. You can't have like two homes. You can't have two folders with the same name in the same space.

00:24:45.125 --> 00:25:03.125
The same thing with namespace collision, right? If you have inputs and you are like me, you don't have original names for all of your inputs, you know, you will eventually have namespace collision because the namespace is shared without modules throughout the whole application.

00:25:03.125 --> 00:25:24.125
By adding the namespace function, and then the module, the two functions work together. Namespace just really appends the name of the module in the UI. And then in the server, you see that as like, it has the same syntax that you would have in a regular server function, right? But it's just reading from the UI from that particular module, that particular input.

00:25:25.125 --> 00:25:34.125
So it's really just appending a bunch of like, you know, prefixes to your inputs. So that way you don't have any namespace collision.

00:25:34.125 --> 00:25:38.125
I think it's like naming your children different things. They all have the same last name.

00:25:38.125 --> 00:25:40.125
Yeah, yeah, exactly.

00:25:40.125 --> 00:25:44.125
I understand the namespace thing, but what is a module?

00:25:44.125 --> 00:25:53.125
A module is just a small piece of interactive code, usually accompanied with, it's like a mini UI server combination, right?

00:25:53.125 --> 00:26:00.125
Yeah, yeah. Self-contained, self-contained. So it's like a Lego piece. Like if you're building a Lego wall.

00:26:01.125 --> 00:26:10.125
I'm drawing a blank too, because I use them so often. It's NS, and then you have module server. Doesn't it read? I can't remember the name of the function inside the server.

00:26:10.125 --> 00:26:18.125
But those two things function like a regular UI and server, but just on a smaller, more modular level, right?

00:26:18.125 --> 00:26:22.125
And you can nest modules, but all that does, again, is just like another subfolder, right?

00:26:22.125 --> 00:26:28.125
Or in Libby's example, it's just a middle name, right? You're further identifying that particular input.

00:26:29.125 --> 00:26:41.125
So you're basically creating a small container that has both client and server reactivity contained within it.

00:26:41.125 --> 00:26:42.125
Yes.

00:26:42.125 --> 00:26:46.125
And then, because of the namespace thing, it's then reusable.

00:26:46.125 --> 00:26:47.125
Yes, yes.

00:26:47.125 --> 00:26:48.125
Okay, so you'll have...

00:26:48.125 --> 00:26:54.125
You'll have your inputs that can then be just read out of your module and then fit into your outputs module.

00:26:54.125 --> 00:26:59.125
That's the piece I was missing, is that it's both in one thing.

00:26:59.125 --> 00:27:04.125
Yes, you have a UI and server component in each module that function just like your regular...

00:27:04.125 --> 00:27:11.125
When you build an app.r file, just your standard boilerplate, that function the same way a UI and server call work there.

00:27:11.125 --> 00:27:14.125
You're just basically making it much more...

00:27:15.125 --> 00:27:20.125
The biggest benefit to using them is just that it mentally chunks a component of the app into, like,

00:27:20.125 --> 00:27:24.125
I'm now only dealing with these inputs and how they're returned.

00:27:24.125 --> 00:27:30.125
Or how you design it, it can be like, I'm only dealing with this input and the output it creates, right?

00:27:30.125 --> 00:27:35.125
Really, module design is kind of up to the individual programmer and the patterns are just preference.

00:27:35.125 --> 00:27:42.125
But the simplest example that I always think of is you have a module for inputs, a module for outputs.

00:27:42.125 --> 00:27:45.125
The input module will return all the outputs.

00:27:45.125 --> 00:27:52.125
And then in the main server, you'll collect those inputs and pass them into the server of the output module.

00:27:52.125 --> 00:27:56.125
Yeah, and what's great is that you...

00:27:56.125 --> 00:27:58.125
It's just like writing functions, right?

00:27:58.125 --> 00:28:00.125
Like, you don't want to repeat yourself.

00:28:00.125 --> 00:28:06.125
You don't want to write the same piece of code for your UI and Shiny over and over again.

00:28:06.125 --> 00:28:10.125
And you're like, oh, well, I'm doing the same thing on this other tab that I did over there twice.

00:28:10.125 --> 00:28:11.125
Just make it a module.

00:28:11.125 --> 00:28:14.125
Use that same module and just change the input or output that you need.

00:28:14.125 --> 00:28:22.125
And like Martin said, like, collect those inputs and outputs in whatever other module you're using for the output.

00:28:22.125 --> 00:28:24.125
But yeah, I think that this is a great conversation.

00:28:24.125 --> 00:28:32.125
If you're interested in modules, there are a couple of great talks by Deepsha Mangani that are recorded that are out there.

00:28:32.125 --> 00:28:34.125
Look up modules, Deepsha Mangani.

00:28:34.125 --> 00:28:38.125
And I will try to get some links in the chat for those as well.

00:28:38.125 --> 00:28:41.125
She does a great job of helping to explain.

00:28:41.125 --> 00:28:42.125
All right.

00:28:42.125 --> 00:28:43.125
Amazing.

00:28:43.125 --> 00:28:46.125
I would say, too, that this is like a...

00:28:46.125 --> 00:28:48.125
I always...

00:28:48.125 --> 00:28:53.125
When you're debugging modules, because the first thing that you're going to wonder, like, what...

00:28:53.125 --> 00:28:54.125
Okay, so what is now...

00:28:54.125 --> 00:28:56.125
What does this look like floating around in my namespace?

00:28:56.125 --> 00:29:05.125
There's a really handy tool, and I do this all the time when I'm dealing with an application that has a lot of modules or nested modules.

00:29:05.125 --> 00:29:10.125
There is a reactive values to list function in Shiny.

00:29:10.125 --> 00:29:17.125
And what you can do is you can just drop that into, like, a render...

00:29:17.125 --> 00:29:18.125
Not render text.

00:29:18.125 --> 00:29:22.125
A render print, and then a verbatim text output.

00:29:22.125 --> 00:29:23.125
Just anywhere in your UI.

00:29:23.125 --> 00:29:25.125
You know, usually at the top level.

00:29:25.125 --> 00:29:28.125
So, like, right at the top of the app.ui.

00:29:28.125 --> 00:29:29.125
Or app.r.

00:29:29.125 --> 00:29:31.125
Sorry, ui.r.

00:29:31.125 --> 00:29:33.125
I forgot we don't do that anymore.

00:29:33.125 --> 00:29:34.125
It's all app.r now.

00:29:34.125 --> 00:29:35.125
It's in your UI.

00:29:35.125 --> 00:29:45.125
You're going to just drop a verbatim text output, and then somewhere down the server, just do a render print of the reactive values to list.

00:29:45.125 --> 00:29:48.125
Just assign it to an object, spit it out in the UI.

00:29:48.125 --> 00:29:54.125
And what that does is it actually gives you a very clear idea of, like, how the namespacing works.

00:29:54.125 --> 00:30:00.125
Because you'll see those appended names of the module to the actual input ID or output ID.

00:30:00.125 --> 00:30:06.125
So, you can actually see all of your reactives in real time without, like, shutting down your app or trying to use the debugger.

00:30:06.125 --> 00:30:14.125
You can just basically spit out the reactive values right in the UI and look at them as you're changing them and moving around.

00:30:14.125 --> 00:30:15.125
Awesome.

