00:38:02.232 --> 00:38:09.353
like, you know, all of these were, they look like decisions on a CV, but it was external forces,

00:38:09.353 --> 00:38:16.073
kind of life batting me around into certain areas more than an active decision. Journalism was,

00:38:16.633 --> 00:38:24.153
I had a friend who I met that I'll go ahead and name him by, he'd be great to have on this.

00:38:24.153 --> 00:38:32.713
Alayshu Bejjak is his name. He and I wrote together at the journalism story bench blog,

00:38:32.713 --> 00:38:38.472
and then he's gone on to work at USA Today. And he was at Urban Institute for a while. I'm not,

00:38:38.472 --> 00:38:45.032
I'm not exactly sure where he is now. But the trade was, I was going to show him how to use R

00:38:45.593 --> 00:38:49.513
and he was going to improve my writing. Because if you've ever been in a graduate program,

00:38:49.513 --> 00:38:54.153
you spend a lot of time writing, you know, articles for peer reviewed research that,

00:38:54.153 --> 00:38:59.993
I hate to break your heart, like no one wants to read. They're all written in passive voice.

00:38:59.993 --> 00:39:04.233
They're all very dry. There's a reason why nobody other than other academics read it. So I

00:39:05.112 --> 00:39:09.513
went to him like desperately looking to improve my writing so people would actually want to read

00:39:09.513 --> 00:39:16.233
what I wrote. And so I think that one of the, one of the things, you know, that one of the things

00:39:16.233 --> 00:39:19.912
that one of the myths you're told is like, oh, the data speaks for itself. You just show them the

00:39:19.912 --> 00:39:25.272
data. And I think that that is a, you know, journalism students and people that are skilled

00:39:25.272 --> 00:39:31.672
with communication know that, you know, you're, you're really trying to, you're working toward

00:39:31.672 --> 00:39:35.993
making sure your audience is engaged and that you're getting them information clearly and

00:39:35.993 --> 00:39:41.112
concisely, you know, and that, that is something that I think when you're trained academically for

00:39:41.112 --> 00:39:48.153
writing, it's, you know, it's almost like volume equals quality. And I think that, you know,

00:39:48.873 --> 00:39:54.953
it's good to have somebody who really, especially nowadays, just in terms of time and economy,

00:39:54.953 --> 00:39:59.513
somebody that can help you get your writing down to a level where you can be clear and concise

00:39:59.513 --> 00:40:05.513
without, without, you know, without removing the important bits. And so journalism was just

00:40:05.593 --> 00:40:11.112
one of the ways that I really wanted to improve my communication, not just, you know, in writing,

00:40:11.112 --> 00:40:16.073
but because so much of what I do is technical writing. I wanted my technical writing to also

00:40:16.073 --> 00:40:21.273
be very clear and concise and written to where, you know, a wide audience could read it and

00:40:21.273 --> 00:40:28.872
understand what was out of it. Amazing. You're, you're in good company. If you are not looking

