There are so many pathways. And then I see one person, I think it was Gonzalo said,

00:40:54.393 --> 00:40:58.233
I tried to get into data science and then fell, fell into being an AI engineer.

00:40:59.032 --> 00:41:03.032
Sometimes the squiggly pathways might start at data science and go somewhere else.

00:41:03.592 --> 00:41:09.113
Yeah, I think honestly, the most interesting, you know, people that did the most interesting

00:41:09.113 --> 00:41:15.353
career paths, it really isn't a like plan. It's this accumulation of unique skills that make them,

00:41:16.073 --> 00:41:21.752
you know, particularly well fit for a type of problem. And, you know, it's, it's that unique

00:41:21.752 --> 00:41:26.793
combination of skills that make you valuable to, you know, to any organization or any field.

00:41:26.793 --> 00:41:31.912
It's not, you know, checking boxes along the way. I mean, I think that, I also think that,

00:41:31.912 --> 00:41:35.673
you know, that there's a great book written about this called range by David Epstein,

00:41:35.673 --> 00:41:41.513
and it was like a followup to Malcolm Blackwell's 10,000 hours. Yeah. It's a phenomenal book that,

00:41:41.513 --> 00:41:45.752
that really points out that like, and we put such an emphasis, especially in technical

00:41:45.752 --> 00:41:55.192
fields on expertise. And, you know, I'm, I'm more of a fan of good enough than I am of expertise.

00:41:55.752 --> 00:42:01.432
I think that good enough, meaning good enough knowledge to get work done, get enough knowledge

00:42:01.752 --> 00:42:07.113
to get, to get what, to get where you need to be is so much more valuable than expertise,

00:42:07.113 --> 00:42:11.912
being an expert in something. We need experts. Absolutely. I'm not, I'm not denying any experts,

00:42:11.912 --> 00:42:16.793
but we don't need everyone to be an expert, right? We need more people that have good enough

00:42:16.793 --> 00:42:23.032
knowledge in a variety of fields. Then we need, you know, a whole bunch of people who are, are

00:42:23.032 --> 00:42:28.472
highly specified in one area. I really think, yeah, general knowledge, good enough knowledge.

00:42:28.472 --> 00:42:32.872
And I think this will just become increasingly true with, you know, all the technological

00:42:33.592 --> 00:42:40.472
advances or changes we see coming is that, you know, the, the, what I've seen thus far with

00:42:40.472 --> 00:42:48.393
the LLM tools is that your, your knowledge around the data science tech stack is going to be much

00:42:48.393 --> 00:42:53.912
more desirable than any particular programming language. You'll still need to know the language,

00:42:53.912 --> 00:43:00.073
but implementing these, you know, across, you know, the technology that is in your ecosystem

00:43:00.073 --> 00:43:04.553
that you work with is going to require knowledge of things outside just your programming language.

00:43:05.353 --> 00:43:10.633
I love that. And you also, I think that having knowledge of multiple things helps you develop

00:43:10.633 --> 00:43:14.872
empathy around the things that other people are dealing with that are adjacent to you.

00:43:14.872 --> 00:43:19.833
And that empathy is very, very important. And it also helps you develop your thinking skills

00:43:19.833 --> 00:43:24.312
so that when someone asks you a case study type of question, when they're like, how would you

00:43:24.312 --> 00:43:27.912
