00:49:13.256 --> 00:49:19.175
developer, and IT org app developer has a lot of overlap, but do you think

00:49:19.175 --> 00:49:24.936
there are any practices from IT org developer that we could learn from a

00:49:24.936 --> 00:49:28.455
data science programmer, Shiny app developer perspective?

00:49:28.455 --> 00:49:31.736
This is a great question for Martin because he actually spent years as a

00:49:32.855 --> 00:49:36.936
Posit admin, sort of in a behind-the-scenes role, but was still

00:49:36.936 --> 00:49:38.936
developing Shiny apps from that direction.

00:49:38.936 --> 00:49:41.736
So you've dealt with this from both sides.

00:49:42.296 --> 00:49:48.775
Yeah, I will say I was frustrated because Shiny app developer, I built

00:49:48.775 --> 00:49:52.936
something in that I'd run into that wall of can't get into production,

00:49:52.936 --> 00:49:53.815
can't deploy it, right?

00:49:53.815 --> 00:49:55.656
So the DevOps kind of wall.

00:49:55.656 --> 00:49:59.416
And then I just decided, you know what?

00:49:59.416 --> 00:50:01.175
I wonder what the problem is.

00:50:01.175 --> 00:50:05.416
So then I went over to the Posit system admin side and realized it's much

00:50:05.416 --> 00:50:06.696
more complicated than I thought it was.

00:50:07.256 --> 00:50:08.296
Like most things.

00:50:08.296 --> 00:50:14.135
So I think that the biggest solution to this is exactly what Libby said, and

00:50:14.135 --> 00:50:22.455
that's understanding more of what IT does and really asking them to go

00:50:22.455 --> 00:50:26.375
through, to the degree that they will let you.

00:50:26.375 --> 00:50:31.175
Some organizations have a very high wall between IT and developers and

00:50:31.175 --> 00:50:36.295
others are, they're able to get in a call and talk through, but understanding

00:50:36.295 --> 00:50:43.095
how these services like Connect and Workbench and Package Manager are set

00:50:43.095 --> 00:50:47.576
up in your organization, understanding how they're configured, understanding

00:50:47.576 --> 00:50:49.815
what maintenance of the services looks like.

00:50:51.095 --> 00:50:54.136
You know, one of the first things that I did as a Posit system admin, because

00:50:54.136 --> 00:50:57.095
I'm a Shiny app developer, was like, all right, obviously a huge part of

00:50:57.095 --> 00:50:58.856
this job is looking at log files.

00:50:59.655 --> 00:51:02.935
It's just a ton of like, you know, grepping on these log files.

00:51:02.935 --> 00:51:09.095
And Shiny has this amazing reactive file reader that I just built a really

00:51:09.095 --> 00:51:14.056
simple Shiny application that just, I could select the log file from the UI

00:51:14.056 --> 00:51:16.535
and just spit the log into the app.

00:51:17.175 --> 00:51:20.136
And then I could search for that instead of having to open the terminal.

00:51:20.136 --> 00:51:20.375
Right.

00:51:20.375 --> 00:51:26.216
So it's, and believe me, that's one of those things that like, unless

00:51:26.216 --> 00:51:30.535
they're really diehard, some people are diehard terminal users and you're

00:51:30.535 --> 00:51:31.895
never going to change your mind.

00:51:31.895 --> 00:51:37.015
But, you know, if you can see what IT deals with and what they do, I think a

00:51:37.015 --> 00:51:41.815
lot of times and approach it from a, hey, I just want to understand, not, you

00:51:41.815 --> 00:51:44.375
know, selfishly, I want to understand what the problem is so I can get my

00:51:44.375 --> 00:51:50.136
stuff deployed, but just understand the difficulties that they deal with from,

00:51:50.136 --> 00:51:53.336
you know, a services and architecture standpoint.

00:51:54.455 --> 00:51:59.336
It'll help you when you're deploying to think about like, okay, what, what

00:51:59.336 --> 00:52:02.856
resources is this going to take up in terms of, you know, what's on the

00:52:02.856 --> 00:52:07.175
server, you know, what, what additional kind of like firewall issues, what

00:52:07.175 --> 00:52:11.416
networking issues might I run into with this application that, you know, IT is

00:52:11.416 --> 00:52:15.496
going to say no, you know, say no to or need approval for, you know, I think

00:52:15.496 --> 00:52:20.776
that just a little bit of understanding of the sysadmin role and

00:52:20.776 --> 00:52:25.576
responsibilities makes you a much better app developer just in terms of like

00:52:25.576 --> 00:52:28.696
that final 10% of getting it into production.

00:52:30.215 --> 00:52:30.456
Yeah.

00:52:30.456 --> 00:52:34.456
And then, you know, I mean, of course, like taking skills back and forth.

00:52:34.456 --> 00:52:39.176
Yeah, I definitely have a different, a different understanding of deploying

00:52:39.176 --> 00:52:43.736
applications after having worked as a system admin and the dependencies and

00:52:43.736 --> 00:52:48.296
stuff that are required, you know, from a, you know, command line dependencies

00:52:48.296 --> 00:52:52.296
that they need to install so that I can use these R packages because the, you

00:52:52.296 --> 00:52:57.095
know, the tools are required on the server itself long before the R package

00:52:57.095 --> 00:52:58.136
will be able to access it.

00:52:59.416 --> 00:52:59.736
Yeah.

00:52:59.736 --> 00:53:04.696
It helps you with the, why can't you just problem because, because nobody

00:53:04.696 --> 00:53:09.736
wants to hear, why can't you just X, Y, Z, because you are not seeing clearly

00:53:09.736 --> 00:53:10.535
their struggles.

00:53:11.335 --> 00:53:16.856
I have a, yeah, I have a basic rule about not ever asking.

00:53:16.856 --> 00:53:22.296
So anybody I work with, I just avoid a just question because I assume everyone

00:53:22.296 --> 00:53:26.696
I work with, all of the just questions have been tried and answered, right?

00:53:26.696 --> 00:53:31.335
So if I find myself thinking, why don't you just, I immediately, they've tried

00:53:31.335 --> 00:53:31.815
that.

00:53:31.815 --> 00:53:32.856
They've already done that.

00:53:32.856 --> 00:53:36.136
If it was a just question, it would have been tried, right?

00:53:36.136 --> 00:53:40.535
So you can come at it with curiosity from a different angle and learn instead of

00:53:40.535 --> 00:53:41.736
like accusing.

00:53:41.736 --> 00:53:44.215
Well, we have reached one minute to top the hour.

